WEBVTT

00:00:10.230 --> 00:00:11.640
Hi.

00:00:11.850 --> 00:00:15.040
Welcome to session 503,
Building Books with iBooks Author.

00:00:15.170 --> 00:00:16.530
My name is Charles Migos.

00:00:16.560 --> 00:00:20.030
I've been the lead designer on the
iBooks project since the very beginning,

00:00:20.030 --> 00:00:23.570
and it's my pleasure to be here today
to teach you a little bit about iBooks

00:00:23.570 --> 00:00:27.070
Author and hopefully leave you guys
with some new skills and tricks and

00:00:27.160 --> 00:00:30.860
techniques to get the most out of
your own book-building experience.

00:00:30.870 --> 00:00:35.210
So first I want to answer the question,
why did we build iBooks Author?

00:00:35.250 --> 00:00:38.100
Of course, we did it for the children.

00:00:38.390 --> 00:00:41.740
We had a vision that the iPad would
be a great platform for delivering

00:00:41.740 --> 00:00:44.890
a new kind of educational material,
one that would kind of transcend the

00:00:44.890 --> 00:00:47.200
limitations of their known counterparts.

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:50.690
You know, you think that textbooks,
they're great at what they do.

00:00:50.700 --> 00:00:53.320
They have densely packed
information captured in text,

00:00:53.350 --> 00:00:55.840
and they're richly
illustrated a lot of the time.

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:58.940
They've evolved over hundreds,
if not thousands of years at this point.

00:00:58.940 --> 00:01:01.220
They're great at what they do.

00:01:01.220 --> 00:01:04.920
And digital publishers have been
excellent at supplying ancillary or

00:01:04.940 --> 00:01:09.200
secondary materials for those textbooks,
and they can be found on the web or as

00:01:09.210 --> 00:01:11.470
standalone applications in various forms.

00:01:11.500 --> 00:01:14.870
But the problem with the systems that
exist today is that when you're taking

00:01:15.150 --> 00:01:18.490
your attention away from the book,
it's a very fragile moment in terms of

00:01:18.540 --> 00:01:22.060
the students understanding the concept
that he or she is trying to learn.

00:01:22.060 --> 00:01:26.540
So every time you make that mode shift
away from a textbook to your computer,

00:01:26.540 --> 00:01:30.550
let's say, to your laptop,
or to some location on the web,

00:01:30.550 --> 00:01:33.340
your connection to what you
were trying to learn is that

00:01:33.340 --> 00:01:34.950
much further away from you.

00:01:34.960 --> 00:01:36.860
So what the iPad does so well
is it ties all these different

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:36.860
types of applications together.

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:38.070
So what the iPad does so well
is it ties all these different

00:01:38.070 --> 00:01:38.860
types of applications together.

00:01:38.860 --> 00:01:42.420
With iBooks multi-touch experience
and the -- an iBooks author

00:01:42.420 --> 00:01:46.600
that enables you to create them,
we supply the best of what textbooks have

00:01:46.690 --> 00:01:51.860
today plus the best of iPad interactivity
and touch experiences coupled with the

00:01:51.950 --> 00:01:54.040
other things the iPad does really well.

00:01:54.040 --> 00:01:58.460
Provides access to the web,
provides access to other applications

00:01:58.460 --> 00:02:01.940
from third-party developers,
and it's really a combination

00:02:01.950 --> 00:02:03.410
that can't be beat.

00:02:04.040 --> 00:02:10.290
And the tool that we created for all
this lovely stuff is iBooks Author.

00:02:10.560 --> 00:02:12.660
And when we were creating this tool,
we were trying to satisfy a

00:02:12.660 --> 00:02:13.930
couple of very tough audiences.

00:02:13.960 --> 00:02:16.900
We had to make sure that the third grade
school teacher that wanted to supply

00:02:16.900 --> 00:02:22.350
custom class materials to his or her
class could walk up and use this product.

00:02:22.360 --> 00:02:25.160
At the same time,
it had to have sufficient depth to

00:02:25.160 --> 00:02:29.540
allow professional publishers to bring
their content to life on the iPad.

00:02:29.540 --> 00:02:32.340
We think we struck kind
of the right balance.

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:34.980
But as we were designing the product,
we knew we were designing it

00:02:34.980 --> 00:02:36.350
for more than just textbooks.

00:02:36.360 --> 00:02:40.300
We were designing it for all kinds of
books that are somewhat visual in nature.

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:41.910
So here I have three examples.

00:02:41.920 --> 00:02:47.800
First is Michelle Obama's American Grown,
which is kind of a slash lifestyle

00:02:47.800 --> 00:02:51.090
cookbook and gardening book all in one.

00:02:51.100 --> 00:02:53.980
Chock full of great
interactive experiences.

00:02:53.980 --> 00:02:56.720
The next is kind of a how-to book,
Learn Guitar.

00:02:56.720 --> 00:02:59.440
It's a great book,
has a lot of video course material to

00:02:59.520 --> 00:03:01.540
help you learn how to play the guitar.

00:03:01.540 --> 00:03:03.850
And the last is The Getty
You're in Focus,

00:03:03.850 --> 00:03:06.300
which is a photographic anthology book.

00:03:06.300 --> 00:03:10.360
So these are all great examples of
those books that aren't well served.

00:03:10.500 --> 00:03:13.340
by traditional EPUB today.

00:03:15.190 --> 00:03:17.860
But you're a highly technical crowd.

00:03:17.860 --> 00:03:20.240
What might iBooks Author have for you?

00:03:20.240 --> 00:03:21.340
What can it offer you?

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:22.750
Well,
many of you out there -- I don't want

00:03:22.850 --> 00:03:25.600
to paint with too broad a brush --
many of you out there are developers.

00:03:25.710 --> 00:03:35.770
You're developing apps like this one,
which is Apple's iPhoto app for iOS.

00:03:35.770 --> 00:03:35.770
You didn't develop that one.

00:03:35.770 --> 00:03:35.770
Maybe some of you did.

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:38.860
And recently what was published
was this multi-touch book,

00:03:38.910 --> 00:03:42.270
Hello iPhoto, which is an excellent
companion to this app.

00:03:42.400 --> 00:03:43.360
This app is very deep.

00:03:43.520 --> 00:03:46.040
It's a powerful photo editing tool.

00:03:46.090 --> 00:03:48.950
This book helps you kind of learn
all of the in-depth secrets and

00:03:48.950 --> 00:03:51.940
the techniques that you need to
kind of get the most out of it.

00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:55.860
It was published by a
third-party developer,

00:03:55.860 --> 00:03:55.860
not by Apple, of course.

00:03:56.400 --> 00:03:58.700
In addition to that,
you might be a game developer.

00:03:58.730 --> 00:04:02.200
Up here I have an example of the
Diablo III Gaming Guide published

00:04:02.330 --> 00:04:03.700
by DK Publishing.

00:04:03.800 --> 00:04:05.300
Who knows your game better than you?

00:04:05.400 --> 00:04:07.900
If you work directly with a writer,
with a designer,

00:04:07.900 --> 00:04:11.870
you could develop your own gaming
walkthrough book or your overall guide.

00:04:12.060 --> 00:04:14.370
Or if you're one of those
brilliant Renaissance types,

00:04:14.450 --> 00:04:17.050
I know you're out there too,
you could do it all yourself.

00:04:17.120 --> 00:04:20.120
And lastly, we have an example of
a technical journal,

00:04:20.140 --> 00:04:23.470
Test Driving iOS Development with
Kiwi from Dan Steinberg.

00:04:23.660 --> 00:04:27.290
If you have domain knowledge and
expertise in a given area that you

00:04:27.300 --> 00:04:30.630
want to make available to the world,
iBooks Author is a great way

00:04:30.750 --> 00:04:32.260
for you to communicate it.

00:04:35.920 --> 00:04:39.450
And lastly,
you might be thinking about an iBook,

00:04:39.620 --> 00:04:42.900
an iBooks multi-touch book,
as an alternative to apps themselves.

00:04:42.920 --> 00:04:45.060
So here we have Cleaning Mona Lisa.

00:04:45.080 --> 00:04:47.140
The author here is Lee Stansted.

00:04:47.140 --> 00:04:50.240
This was developed by Tappity.

00:04:50.240 --> 00:04:52.770
They developed all the
interactive content for this book.

00:04:52.780 --> 00:04:55.270
And Jeremy Olson from
Tappity had this to say.

00:04:55.280 --> 00:04:59.440
He said, Olson suggests, well actually,
sorry, this is him being quoted.

00:04:59.620 --> 00:05:02.980
He guesses that using iBooks
Author offered them a factor of five,

00:05:02.980 --> 00:05:04.910
six,
or even seven times improvement in man

00:05:04.910 --> 00:05:06.960
hours versus traditional app development.

00:05:06.960 --> 00:05:09.790
That's really telling of what
you can do with iBooks Author,

00:05:09.810 --> 00:05:14.620
and the kind of experiences you can
get with iBooks multi-touch books.

00:05:14.620 --> 00:05:18.020
And this quote comes
courtesy of tuaw.com.

00:05:20.580 --> 00:05:21.770
So what are we going to learn today?

00:05:21.840 --> 00:05:25.190
Well, first I'm going to give you a demo
of the iBooks multi-touch experience.

00:05:25.200 --> 00:05:29.900
This will be familiar to many of you,
but I'm going to touch on aspects

00:05:29.900 --> 00:05:34.240
of the experience that we'll
showcase again in iBooks Author.

00:05:34.340 --> 00:05:36.970
So we're going to get an overview
of the basics of the interface,

00:05:36.970 --> 00:05:39.420
the iBooks Author interface,
and its features,

00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:42.060
and then I'm going to give you some
kind of more in-depth knowledge so you

00:05:42.060 --> 00:05:45.400
can really just give you some tools
and techniques that will help you

00:05:45.400 --> 00:05:50.190
differentiate your content from the
rest of the books on the iBookstore.

00:05:53.500 --> 00:06:00.040
All right,
so let's take a look at iBooks.

00:06:00.610 --> 00:06:04.230
All right, so as I launch iBooks,
this is the bookshelf that

00:06:04.260 --> 00:06:05.640
we've come to know and love.

00:06:05.640 --> 00:06:07.120
On it, I have a selection of books.

00:06:07.120 --> 00:06:08.160
Most of them are multi-touch.

00:06:08.160 --> 00:06:11.680
A couple of them are traditional ePubs.

00:06:11.880 --> 00:06:14.640
I'm going to go ahead
and launch one of them.

00:06:19.630 --> 00:06:23.210
And at outset, you can see that this is a
vastly different experience

00:06:23.340 --> 00:06:24.570
